node.title: Mind Meld w/ Ian Bremmer: Economics vs Saving lives

node.text:
Here are the facts:

Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) usually begins with a fever and a dry cough, maybe a headache, like you are getting a cold. Sneezing is uncommon.

Within days, you feel like you’ve got the flu, with a high fever, aches and pains. Sometimes you can feel like you are recovering - until the pneumonia starts. Your lungs can’t get enough oxygen and you develop crepitance. That’s when your lungs crackle because there’s not enough surfactant (soapy oils). Think of a balloon that’s wet on the inside. Because the virus also attacks the heart, pericarditis can also occur in the late stages, leading to cardiogenic shock and death due to cardiac arrest.

As of March 16th, more than 6,400 people globally have died. There are more than 164,000 confirmed cases in at least 146 countries/territories, according to the World Health Organization. 
Fatality frequency is between 0.7% - 6%, depending on the number of tests that are done & the number of critical care units available in the region.

The R0, the number of people that a carrier infects, is between 2 to 4. That means that for every 1 person that contracts the virus, at least 2 to 4 will become infected. 
In the US, we expect a doubling of cases every 6 days. That means we are looking at 1 million cases by the end of April.

Then 2 million by May 7

Then 4 million by May 13

If we do nothing. We are no longer able to wipe this virus off the face of the planet by containment, so currently, the strategy is 2-fold — flatten & delay:

1. We need to flatten the curve rate of infection to help ease the pressure on our healthcare system. We need young people especially to help us fight this by staying inside and self quarantining.

2. Somewhere between 33% and 75% of us will catch this disease, unless we can delay it until a vaccine trial is successful, which is another 18 months away, assuming it works. I am hopeful but, until then, we have to live with corona.

Ultimately, we will get to what’s called a “herd immunity”. That means that enough of us have developed a resistance to COVID-19 that the R0 is less than one. When that happens, it should eventually peter out. 
Continue reading in comments 👇

node.text:
DNA is NOT our destiny. Our future health depends on us!
💪 
A 2018 Harvard study that looked at over 100,000 people’s lives found those who do the basic things - don’t smoke, don’t drink too much, eat sensibly and exercise - can expect to live a decade longer and in much better health
💪
And that’s the easy, obvious stuff
💪 
Imagine what could be achieved by doing all the right stuff
.
.
#sinclairlab #health #healthylifestyle #healthyfood #agingbackwards #aginggracefully #fitness #science #research #diet #fasting #exercise #bodybuilding

node.text:
Looks like we finally have control over the aging process in the human brain, at least in these mini-human brains.
🧠
These cute little fellas, called organoids, actually have brain waves! They take a few months to grow, coaxed from reprogrammed human skin cells.
🧠
Some of the organoids we grow have a mutation that accelerates Alzheimer’s in people, allowing us to study the effect of aging & age reversal in the context of this terrible disease.
🧠 
We are excited about the possibility of reversing the age of the brain to recover the ability to heal, learn, and recall lost memories!
🧠
Credit to Jae-Hyun Yang for these brains and the photo @sinclair_lab

🧬 

☄️ 

🚀 

#sinclairlab #sinclair_lab #science #hubermanlab #alzheimers #dementia #hacking #harvard #harvardmedicalschool #research #medicine #biotechnology #future #davidasinclair #davidsinclairphd

node.text:
Resveratrol and quercetin reduce the levels of the toxic molecule methylglyoxal and protect rat kidneys from the effects of high glucose in the bloodstream (type 2 diabetes). Link to article in bio

For healthy kidneys: 
1. Eat less salt
2. Choose lower potassium foods. 
3. Limit protein. High-protein foods include lean meats, eggs, milk, cheese and beans. Low-protein foods include vegetables, fruits, breads and cereals.

About 1 out of 3 adults with diabetes has kidney disease. The main job of the kidneys is to filter wastes and extra water out of your blood to make urine. Your kidneys also help control blood pressure and make hormones.

To check for kidney disease, health care providers use a blood test that checks how well your kidneys are filtering your blood, called GFR, which stands for glomerular filtration rate. They may also do a urine test to check for albumin, a protein that can pass into the urine when the kidneys are damaged. 

A eGFR below 60 for three months or more or a eGFR above 60 with kidney damage (marked by high levels of albumin in your urine) indicates chronic kidney disease

Video: thanks @bayerus  @mayoclinic

node.text:
A cheaper way to experience zero G, but without the view 🚀 Thanks @mitpics & Zero G for letting me tag along on 12 parabola flights. How does it feel? Like someone switched off gravity for 30 seconds. No queasiness, just a hell of a lot of fun. @raycronise @gozerog and @peterdiamandis @xprize: luv u guys! 🙏 
.
.
.
.
#space #virgingalactic #zerogravity #fun #science #livingmybestlife #xprize #fitness #flight #spacex #branson #richardbranson

Spent time with my friend Chris Williamson to chat about the meaning of life and what it can be like with not a lot of effort 💪 link in bio 
.
.
.
@chriswillx @modernwisdomlife 
#health #success #aging #fasting #longevity #fitness #sleep #stamina #beauty #longevidad #happiness

node.text:
Almost crying with happiness, feeling deep gratitude on the day the nation was born, to have made the USA my home and seen my three kids grow into the adults I’d hoped they’d become. After an incredibly challenging and emotional year for us, today was the first day that finally felt normal. Alex, Benjamin & Natalie (pictured), I love you very, very much

.

.

#grateful #happiness #parenting #independenceday #longevity #love #joy #gratitude #daddysgirl #talent

node.text:
Researchers agree that you can alter your pace of aging by doing the right things. Just avoiding smoking, eating right and less often, exercising and getting sleep is sufficient to add 14 years. And that’s not including the more advanced approaches I describe in Lifespan (link in bio)

#health #healthylifestyle #longevity #fitness #fitnessmotivation #medicine #rogan #food

So enjoyed this chat with the one and only Whitney Cummings. I too had been looking forward to this discussion for years. Thankfully it was not derailed by the coffee spill....we talk health biotrackers, things that age us physically and mentally, the benefits and detriments of stress, challenges in science, and much more. Whitney, Thank you for one heck of a good time! Can’t wait for round 2! Link in bio
